traction, transatlantic migrations, armed rebellion, and American judicial intervention offers both a historical antecedent and allegory for contemporary global capitalism's reconfiguration of culture and subjectivity. At the same time, he shows how the mutineers' example provides a model for imagining utopian forms of transnationalism. With its wide-ranging comparative approach, Rebellious Histories brings a unique perspective to the study of the cultural histories of both slave resistance and globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAntislavery movements -- United States. 0aAntislavery movementszUnited States. 0aInfluence (Literary, artistic, etc.) -- History -- 20th century. 0aInfluence (Literary, artistic, etc.)xHistoryy20th century. 0aSierra Leone -- History. 0aSierra Leonean literature. 0aSlave insurrections -- United States. 0aSlave insurrectionszUnited States. 4aArea Studies : African Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aHistory : Industrial / Labor Relations. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aSociology : Social Change. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Slavery.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438439716423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438439716/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles